1 Task 1: Data Source

This data is from NBA statistics. championsdata.csv contains game-by-game team totals for the championship team from every finals game between 1980 and 2017. The 1980 NBA Finals was the first Finals series since the NBA added the three point line. Dataset uploeaded to kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/) as a open source dataset by Dave Rosenman.

# ... with 12 more variables: FT <int>, FTA <int>, FTP <dbl>, ORB <int>,
#   DRB <int>, TRB <int>, AST <int>, STL <int>, BLK <int>, TOV <int>, PF
#   <int>, PTS <int>
#Actually the games missing TPP(three points percentage) has 0 TP(three points made),
#so I would simply replace those NA with 0 which makes sense. 
#Since One cannot have a TPP other than 0 when TP is 0.
cd$TPP[which(is.na(cd$TPP) == TRUE)] = 0
cd <- cd %>%
  mutate(Win = factor(Win, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("loss", "win")),
         Home = factor(Home, levels = c(0,1), labels = c("Away", "Home")),
         #create a new variable "OT" based on if the game went over time or no.
         IS_OT = factor(ifelse(MP > 240, 1,0), levels = c(0,1), labels = c("N", "Y")),
         Game = factor(Game)) %>%
  select(Year, Team, Game, Win, Home, FGA, FGP, TPA, TPP, FTA, FTP, 
         TRB, AST, STL, TOV, PF, PTS, IS_OT)

I dropped the first column which is just a number of row, detected missing values and imputed with reasonable value, changed variable type from integer to factor for Win, Home, and Game, made a new factor variable IS_OT based on if the game went over time or no.

4 Task 4: Code Book

a <- dput(names(cd))
c("Year", "Team", "Game", "Win", "Home", "FGA", "FGP", "TPA", 
"TPP", "FTA", "FTP", "TRB", "AST", "STL", "TOV", "PF", "PTS", 
"IS_OT")
b <- c("The year the series was played", "Team: The name of the team", 
       "Game: Game #", "Win: 1 = Win. 0 = Loss", 
       "Home: 1 = Home team. 0 = Away team", "Field goal attempts", 
       "Field goal percentage", "Three point attempts", 
       "Three point percentage", "Free throws attempted", 
       "Free throw percentage", "Total rebounds", 
       "Assists", "Steals", "Turnovers", 
       "Personal fouls", "Points scored", "Overtime or no")
c <- map(cd, function(x) class(x))
d <- map(cd, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
e <- map(cd, function(x) ifelse(is.factor(x) == T, "--", min(x, na.rm=T)))
f <- map(cd, function(x) ifelse(is.factor(x) == T, "--", max(x, na.rm=T)))

cd.CB <- data_frame(Variable = a, Description = b, Class = c, Missing = d, Min = e, Max = f)

5 Task 5: My Subjects

These data describes NBA final series statistics of the final winner team of the championship of the year from year 1980 to year 2017. Each row contains data from a game.

6 Task 6: My Variables

Year: - The year the series was played.

Team: - The name of the team.

Win: -Result of win or loss: 1 = Win. 0 = Loss

Home: -Status of home: 1 = Home team. 0 = Away team.

Game: - Game number in the final series.

FGA - Field goal attempts.

FGP - Field goal percentage.

TPA - Three point attempts.

TPP - Three point percentage.

FTA - Free throws attempted.

FTP - Free throw percentage.

TRB - Total rebounds.

AST - Total assists.

STL - Total steals.

TOV - Total turnovers of the whole team.

PF - Total personal fouls.

PTS - Total points scored.

IS_OT - If the game went over time or not.

pairs(cd, lower.panel = panel.smooth)

From the pair plot matrix, we can see that the pts is hightly corralated with FGA, FGP, and AST, and for categorical variables, total points is a little higher when the team is winning and the game did not go overtime.

p1 <- ggplot(cd, aes(AST, PTS, color = Win)) +
  geom_point()
p2 <- ggplot(cd, aes(AST, PTS, color = IS_OT)) +
  geom_point()
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = c(1))

plot(cd$Game, cd$PTS, type = "o")
abline(lm(cd$PTS ~ cd$Game), lwd = 2, col = "red")
